Joshua Tlatelpa-Agustin, Jerry Zhang, Anton Burtsev
is a bucket that contains 4 kvs
is a 16 bytes key and value pair
Prefetch engine is implemented as a ring buffer, where
queue head advances when item entering queue, and queue
tail advances when item leavs the queue
Prefetch engine computes hash of the KV pair upon entering the queue,
and prefetch the corresponding cacheline in the hashtable.
DRAMHiT uses prefetch engine to prefetch workload and
do operations in batch manner after all items in queue has
been prefetched. It uses linear probing to resolve collisions.
We observe that on uniform distribution, DRAMHiT experiences 1.3
reprobe per find operation on average at 70% fill factor. Thus, Multilevel
hashtable intends to reduce the spill problem by adding an additional
level that contains buckets. Each bucket represents a cacheline with 4 key
values. When a bucket is full, we will insert into the second level where
the implementation is identical as a regular DRAMHiT.
add new kv index back to queue if spill
Under this collision scheme, a given kv pair could potentially
spill over a cacheline, and in order to preserve principle of
never accessing unprefetch memory, DRAMHiT will add kv
back to the prefetch engine with spill over index.
On find operation, we uses SIMD hardware support on x86 to look
up multiple kvs. Because buckets are cache aligned, SIMD technique
is also more efficient than regular DRAMHiT.
